# Key Findings

## Row

### Main Insights

- The overall subscription rate is relatively low, which means the campaign had a large class imbalance between customers who subscribed and customers who did not subscribe.
- Subscription rates differ across customer segments, especially by age group and job type.
- Campaign timing matters because subscription rates vary by month.
- Contact method is associated with different subscription rates, suggesting that the way customers are contacted can influence campaign performance.
- Customers with longer call durations are more likely to subscribe, but duration should be interpreted carefully because it is only known after the call happens.
- Previous campaign contact and broader economic indicators also appear to be related to subscription outcomes.

### Marketing Recommendation

Based on this dashboard, the bank should focus on customer segments and campaign conditions with higher subscription rates instead of contacting all customers equally. A more targeted campaign strategy could improve efficiency by prioritizing stronger customer segments, better-performing months, and more effective contact methods.
